0.02593104,-0.0421664,-0.01924072,-0.01884431,0.00463447,-0.05922332,0.01127664,0.00349637,0.0236167,-0.00422875,0.02860484,0.01157689,-0.01749915,-0.02188169,-0.01819842,0.07970977,0.02729906,-0.04261492,0.04236223,-0.01701374,-0.01481951,0.00987767,0.03883672,-0.03720115,-0.02941241,0.00937947,0.00965594,-0.06567851,-0.01385232,0.03425143,-0.0130369,-0.00537774,0.00229648,0.03791948,0.06014851,-0.00104969,0.07604652,0.00136151,0.00333904,-0.00818206,0.00159342,0.01878345,0.0017246,0.01411795,-0.03184467,-0.03132679,-0.06202189,-0.0289413,-0.01352654,0.05986167,0.0814057,-0.00874418,-0.02031406,-0.07578648,-0.0307841,-0.00640975,0.0473686,-0.01225579,-0.01366962,-0.06417719,-0.02227739,-0.01216862,0.0231775,0.00609151,0.05268108,0.0069941,-0.01673671,-0.00942502,-0.0062915,-0.06849071,0.01909338,-0.02559428,0.00758433,0.00517953,0.02131189,0.01961837,0.00388538,-0.02355493,0.01011115,0.03820691,-0.02221505,-0.04718884,0.03631159,-0.02983245,0.00015521,-0.00927481,-0.08018788,-0.06091537,0.01056937,0.00258463,0.04193281,-0.02616119,-0.0132333,0.00228041,0.03760889,-0.00519084,0.07907197,-0.00148213,0.01536629,0.00177435,0.08271447,-0.10970807,0.03015268,-0.00164486,-0.00345586,0.0553582,0.00239905,-0.01337224,-0.08747081,0.0463644,0.03052481,0.01489489,-0.03160435,-0.02338956,0.00000121,-0.01491454,-0.00083156,-0.09679799,0.00439196,0.01345039,-0.01539642,0.00816634,-0.07357527,0.01968827],"last_embed":{"hash":"5b5680d2311bf19c4a2cc0ca42e889b6b90e1f9b7f1ca41cf9b6bf041c430206","tokens":7380}}},"last_read":{"hash":"5b5680d2311bf19c4a2cc0ca42e889b6b90e1f9b7f1ca41cf9b6bf041c430206","at":1742533449690},"class_name":"SmartSource","outlinks":[{"title":"A deep model has power because it contains the central concepts and abstractions that can succinctly and flexibly express essential knowledge of the users’ activities, their problems, and their solutions. The first step is to somehow represent the essential concepts of the domain in the model. Refinement comes later, after successive iterations of knowledge crunching and refactoring. But this process really gets into gear when an important concept is recognized and made explicit in the model and design.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":1},{"title":"succinctly","target":"succinctly","line":3},{"title":"crunch","target":"crunch","line":4},{"title":"Many transformations of domain models and the corresponding code happen when developers recognize a concept that has been hinted at in discussion or present implicitly in the design, and they then represent it explicitly in the model with one or more objects or relationships.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":7},{"title":"The UBIQUITOUS LANGUAGE is made up of the vocabulary that pervades speech, documents, model diagrams, and even code. If a term is absent from the design, it is an opportunity to improve the model and design by including it.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":11},{"title":"pervade","target":"pervade","line":12},{"title":"The booking application used a routing engine to plan the trip for a cargo. Each leg of the journey was stored in a row of a database table, indicating the ID of the vessel voyage (a particular voyage by a particular ship)slated to carry the cargo, the location where it would be loaded, and the location where it would be unloaded.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":16},{"title":"Scrutinize Awkwardness","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":21},{"title":"Sometimes it can be hard to recognize that there even is a missing concept. You may have objects doing all the work but find some of the responsibilities awkward. Or, if you do realize something is missing, a model solution may elude you.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":23},{"title":"elude","target":"elude","line":25},{"title":"Now you have to actively engage the domain experts in the search.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":28},{"title":"We still have more cases we’ve been holding back.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":33},{"title":"Actually, the interest calculation would be simpler if it was done just for one day, or period.And then we could just hang on to them all.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":36},{"title":"With this model, we get the interest calculation, or rather, the accrual calculation logic thatwas in the Interest Calculator separated from tracking. And I hadn’t noticed until now how much duplication there is in the Fee Calculator. Also, now the different kinds of fees can easily be added.Expert: Yes, the calculation was correct before, but I can see everything now.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":39},{"title":"accrual","target":"accrual","line":40},{"title":"She could see the awkwardness of the interest calculations and made a committed effort to look for a deeper answer.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":43},{"title":"committed","target":"committed","line":44},{"title":"With a more passive source of expertise, she would have made more false starts and depended more on other developers as brainstorming partners.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":46},{"title":"Contemplate Contradictions","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":50},{"title":"contemplate","target":"contemplate","line":51},{"title":"contradictions","target":"contradictions","line":52},{"title":"Such pesky contradictions, which we encounter all the time when digging into program requirements, can be great clues to deeper models.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":54},{"title":"But there is a residue where two factual statements by experts seem to contradict.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":57},{"title":"residue","target":"residue","line":58},{"title":"From this he deduced an early form of the idea of inertial frames of reference, solving theparadox and leading to a much more useful model of the physics of motion.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":60},{"title":"Even so, this same pattern of thought often helps pierce the superficial layers of a problem domain into a deeper insight.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":62},{"title":"Don’t overlook the obvious when seeking model concepts.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":64},{"title":"In this scenario, the developer couldn’t turn to the expert for a brainstorming session to probe for the missing concepts she suspected to be lurking under the surface.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":68},{"title":"Accrual Basis Accounting. This method recognizes income when it is earned, even if it is not paid.All expenses also show when they are incurred whether they have been paid for or billed to be paid at alater date. Any obligation due, including taxes, will be shown as expense.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":71},{"title":"Such reading would not have provided an off-the-shelf solution. It would have given several new starting points for her own experiments, along with the distilled experience of people who have traveled the territory. She would have been spared reinventing the wheel.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":75},{"title":"The examples I’ve given don’t convey the amount of trial and error involved. I might follow half a dozen leadsin conversation before finding one that seems clear and useful enough to try out in the model. I’ll end upreplacing that one at least once later, as additional experience and knowledge crunching serve up better ideas. Amodeler/designer cannot afford to get attached to his own ideas.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":79},{"title":"Eachrefactoring leaves the design more supple, easier to change the next time, ready to bend in the places that turn to need to bend","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":83},{"title":"There really is no choice, anyway. Experimentation is the way to learn what works and doesn’t. Trying toavoid missteps in design will result in a lower quality result because it will be based on less experience. And itcan easily take longer than a series of quick experiments.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":86},{"title":"Factoring the constraint into its own method allows us to give itan intention-revealing name that makes the constraint explicit in our design. It is now a named thing we candiscuss.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":89},{"title":"Here are some warning signs that a constraint is distorting the design of its host object.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":93},{"title":"768","target":"booknote/books-data/resources/(annots)Domain-Driven Design Tackling Complexity in the Heart of Software by Eric Evans (z-lib.org).pdf/p165r100.750,341.490,561.770,433.080z2i(42729ef6-5417-aead-d7ac-d42ca1a94b0a).png#center","line":96},{"title":"When the constraints are obscuring the object’s basic responsibility, or when the constraint is prominent in the domain yet not prominent in the model, you can factor it out into an explicit object or even model it as a set of objects and relationships.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":98},{"title":"(Experience has taught shipping firms that this overbooking compensates for last-minute cancellations, so their ships will sail nearly full.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":101},{"title":"Right up front, let’s agree that we do not want to make procedures a prominent aspect of our model.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":104},{"title":"The first example in this chapter described a shipping system that routed cargo. This routing process wassomething with business meaning. A SERVICE is one way of expressing such a process explicitly, while stillencapsulating the extremely complex algorithms.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":106},{"title":"The key to distinguishing a process that ought to be made explicit from one that should be hidden is simple: Isthis something the domain experts talk about, or is it just part of the mechanism of the computer program?","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":108},{"title":"SPECIFICATION provides a concise way of expressing certain kinds of rules,extricating them from conditional logic and making them explicit in the model.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":110},{"title":"Predicates are functions that evaluate to “true” or “false” and can be combined using operators such as “AND” and “OR” to express more complex rules.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":112},{"title":"predicate","target":"predicate","line":113},{"title":"As appealing as the idea is, full implementation of logic in objects is a major undertaking. (After all, logic programming is a whole modeling and design paradigm in its own right.)","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":115},{"title":"To put it another way, the new object is a specification. A SPECIFICATION states a constraint on the state of another object, which may or may not be present. It has multiple uses, but one that conveys the most basic concept is that a SPECIFICATION can test any object to see if it satisfies the specified criteria.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":118},{"title":"The SPECIFICATION keeps the rule in the domain layer. Because the rule is a full-fledged object, the design can be a more explicit reflection of the model.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":121},{"title":"A SPECIFICATION can be given the information it will need to do its job in a simple, straightforward way.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":125},{"title":"Relational databases have powerful search capabilities. How can we take advantage of that power to solve this problem efficiently while retaining the model of a SPECIFICATION? MODEL-DRIVEN DESIGN demands that the model stay in lockstep with the implementation, but it allows freedom to choose any implementation that faithfully captures the meaning of the model. Lucky for us, SQL is a very natural way to write SPECIFICATIONS.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":128},{"title":"SPECIFICATIONS mesh smoothly with REPOSITORIES, which are the building-block mechanisms for providing query access to domain objects and encapsulating the interface to the database","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":130},{"title":"The REPOSITORY now has a very specialized query that most likely will be used only in this case. That is acceptable, but depending on the relative numbers of Invoices that are overdue compared to those that are delinquent, an intermediate solution that leaves the REPOSITORY methods more generic may still give goodperformance, while keeping the SPECIFICATION more self-explanatory.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":133},{"title":"We’ll take a performance hit with this code, because we pull out more Invoices and then have to select fromthem in memory.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":136},{"title":"Whether this is an acceptable cost for the better factoring of responsibility depends entirelyon circumstances.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":139},{"title":"Sometimes, to improve performance, or more likely to tighten security, queries may be implemented on the server as stored procedures. In that case, the SPECIFICATION could carry only the parameters allowed by the stored procedure. For all that, there is no difference in the model between these various implementations. The choice of implementation is free except where specifically constrained by the model. The price comes in a more cumbersome way of writing and maintaining queries.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":141},{"title":"The interface is more flexible, or can be enhanced with more flexibility, because the statement of the request is in the hands of the client, while the generator is only obligated to fulfill the letter of the SPECIFICATION.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":144},{"title":"Building to order can mean creation of an object from scratch, but it can also be a configuration of preexisting objects to satisfy the SPEC.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":147},{"title":"A small team ofdevelopers and business experts have split off and have set to work on it, but they haven’t even begun to code","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":151},{"title":"They are trying to design for the anticipated Packer.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":154},{"title":"With the domain objects and SERVICE interface made in the warehouse packer example, the application team realizes they could build a very simple implementation of a Packer that could help the development process move along, allowing work to go forward in parallel and closing the feedback loop, which only reaches full effect with a working end-to-end system.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":156},{"title":"One team has to wait for working code from another in order to move forward. Both teams have to wait for full integration to exercise their components or get feedback from users. This kind of congestion can often be eased by a MODEL-DRIVEN prototype of a key component,even if it does not satisfy all requirements. When implementation is decoupled from interface,then having any working implementation at all allows flexibility for project work to go in parallel. When the time is right, the prototype can be replaced by a more effective implementation. In the meantime, all other parts of the system have something to interact with **during development.**","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":160},{"title":"They also keep the interface up-to-date with their latest design, forcing refactoring of the application, and some domain objects, thereby tackling the integration problems early.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":164},{"title":"Here we have an example of a “simplest thing that could possibly work” that actually becomes possible because of a more sophisticated model. We can have a functioning prototype of a very complex component in a couple dozen lines of easily understood code. A less MODEL-DRIVEN approach would be harder to understand,would be harder to upgrade (because the Packer would be more coupled to the rest of the design), and in this case, would likely take longer to prototype.","target":"obsidian://booknote?type=annotation&book=resources/Domain-Driven%20Design%20Tackling%20Complexity%20in%20the%20Heart%20of%20Software%20by%20Eric%20Evans%20(z-lib.org","line":168}],"blocks":{"#":[1,171]},"last_import":{"mtime":1654960831620,"size":28734,"at":0,"hash":"5b5680d2311bf19c4a2cc0ca42e889b6b90e1f9b7f1ca41cf9b6bf041c430206"},"key":"DDD 的实战（第九章）.md"},
